      <hedline>
        <hl1>In Need of Care</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Dr Richard G Roberts (American Academy of Family Physicians) deplores shortage of primary care physicians in America and the fact that many uninsured and underinsured families lack primary care physician (Oct 25 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Emergency Room, to Many, Remains the Doctor's Office'' (front page, Oct. 25):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Emergency Room, to Many, Remains the Doctor's Office'' (front page, Oct. 25):</p>
        <p>I have cared for the uninsured and underinsured for 20 years. Many don't seek primary care because they can't afford to, and end up with otherwise preventable medical crises; others put off their own exams so they can pay for their children's; and most live in fear of being impoverished by medical bills.</p>
        <p>Another barrier for many families is the profound shortage of primary care physicians in America -- the doctors who are specially trained to keep families healthy. Only 28 percent of America's doctors are trained in primary care, and that number is dropping.</p>
        <p>Until we address both of these problems, America's patients will continue to suffer from inadequate care.</p>
        <p>RICHARD G. ROBERTS, M.D.  President, American Academy  of Family Physicians  Belleville, Wis., Oct. 26, 2000</p>
      </block>
